column6: in the garden of eden story, God never locks the gates after casting Adam and Eve out. he places angels with flaming swords to guard the way to the tree of life, but the entrance remains open. this isn't a mistake in the text. it's a hopeful promise hidden in our darkest story. paradise was never sealed shut. the path home has always remained. the way back is never blocked. just guarded until we are ready to return.
column55: father. husband. look at children's eyes, they still remember how to see

column6: a child falls, and their first cry is from disbelief, not pain - bodies betraying what minds trusted. this same shock lives in adult grief. in heartbreak. in prayers that go unanswered. not that life hurts, but that it continues hurting after we've begged it to stop. the wild miracle isn't finding joy in perfect things but in watching hands that have buried loved ones still plant gardens. still hold babies. still reach for another dawn. there is no explaining this stubborn hope. it lives in bones, not thoughts. it outlasts logic. outlasts faith.

We just launched the Payman Dev Challenge. 

No boring fintech. 
No theoretical AI.

column6:
Here's a simple explanation of KBLaM:

Large language models (LLMs) are great at understanding and generating text, but they struggle to use outside information effectively. Current methods to add knowledge to LLMs have problems: they‚Äôre either expensive, complicated, or slow when dealing with lots of data.

KBLaM (Knowledge Base-Augmented Language Model) is a new way to solve this. It adds structured knowledge‚Äîlike facts organized into simple categories‚Äîdirectly into an LLM without needing extra tools or retraining the whole model. It does this by turning facts into special pairs of data (keys and values) that the model can understand and use efficiently.

Here‚Äôs how it works simply:

Organizing Knowledge: Facts (e.g., ‚Äúthe sky is blue‚Äù) are turned into a format the model can process.

Using It: The model can then pull out the right facts to answer questions without extra steps.

Why it‚Äôs cool:

It‚Äôs fast and doesn‚Äôt slow down as you add more knowledge.

You can update the facts anytime without starting over.

It helps the model give better, more trustworthy answers and even say ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know‚Äù when it doesn‚Äôt have the info.

Here's a simple explanation of KBLaM:

Large language models (LLMs) are great at understanding and generating text, but they struggle to use outside information effectively. Current methods to add knowledge to LLMs have problems: they‚Äôre either expensive, complicated, or slow when dealing with lots of data.

KBLaM (Knowledge Base-Augmented Language Model) is a new way to solve this. It adds structured knowledge‚Äîlike facts organized into simple categories‚Äîdirectly into an LLM without needing extra tools or retraining the whole model. It does this by turning facts into special pairs of data (keys and values) that the model can understand and use efficiently.

Here‚Äôs how it works simply:

Organizing Knowledge: Facts (e.g., ‚Äúthe sky is blue‚Äù) are turned into a format the model can process.

Mixing It In: These facts are added to the model‚Äôs ‚Äúattention‚Äù system‚Äîthe part that decides what‚Äôs important‚Äîusing a clever trick that keeps things fast and simple.

Using It: The model can then pull out the right facts to answer questions without extra steps.

Why it‚Äôs cool:

It‚Äôs fast and doesn‚Äôt slow down as you add more knowledge.

You can update the facts anytime without starting over.

It helps the model give better, more trustworthy answers and even say ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt know‚Äù when it doesn‚Äôt have the info.

Think of it like giving an LLM a smart, easy-to-use library of facts it can check instantly. This could make AI better for things like medicine or science, where being accurate matters a lot. The team behind it is sharing their work so others can build on it, hoping to make AI smarter and more reliable in the future!

column6: At a purely vibes level, this seems like the right approach for characterizing AI progress. I also suspect it's a reason why evals saturate so quickly ‚Äì evals are typically questions at one particular timescale, and saturate when models master staying coherent at that timescale.
column55: Please tweet at me with CUDA performance tips.

column6: This seems to me to be a really important new form of meta-eval. The experience of AIs very much is that they're superhuman at the scale of seconds (*I* don't know the CLI syntax of every program off the top of my head), like a top human at 5 minutes, but mediocre at >30 minutes.

column6: But that‚Äôs very much not the case. The accuracy varies dramatically based on which numbers I pick. It‚Äôs good at 5.3-5.2 but bad at 5.8-5.11. So the sampling mechanism matters.

column172: AI tweet bot.

column6: You don‚Äôt actually need the sample to be random per se. You need the sampling mechanism to be uncorrelated from the outcome Y. That would be true if for example LLMs were calculator. Then it wouldn‚Äôt matter how I choose the numbers, I‚Äôd estimate 100% accuracy and I‚Äôd be right.
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: Even if it is, how do you take a random sample from it?
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: But going back to the start, ignoring all this other stuff, I‚Äôm seeing people talk about some insane T‚Äôs, like ‚ÄúT is the set of tasks that it takes a human expert less than one hour to perform‚Äù. Is this even well-defined?
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: And the truth is, the choice of S and Y matters a lot even for trivial tasks like arithmetic. If it didn't matter, the LLM could multiply equally well no matter how it's asked, then this wouldn't be a such a big deal. But empirically, how you ask and how you interpret matters.
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: So even with this relatively simple and well-behaved case of 6-digit multiplication, the best we can do is to estimate the accuracy E[Y(L(S(t)))] for a fixed pair of translators S and Y. But there are effectively infinitely many possible translators S and Y.
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: So, we pick a task t. We translate it into text using some function, let's call it S(t). We get back some text from the llm, say L(S(t)). Finally, we translate that text into an indicator, where 1 represents a correct answer. Call that Y(L(S(t))).
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6:
On the flip side, the LLM doesn't simply return a completed task, per se; it returns text. You might get back:

- "221"
- "13 √ó 17 = 221"
- "The product of 13 and 17 is: \boxed{221}"
- ...
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6:
But even if T is 6 multiplication, it's worth questioning the idea that we can sample from T. You don't give an LLM a task directly. You give it text. There are many ways to translate it into text. 
- "What's 13 √ó 17?"
- "13 √ó 17"
- "You are smart. What is 13 √ó 17?"
- ...
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: If T is being a lawyer or writing code or handling customer service interactions then it seems somewhere between incredibly difficult and impossible to randomly sample from T.
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: Of course this is where statistics comes in. If you can randomly sample from T, then you can use statistics to say something about the accuracy on all of T based on a sample from T. But *can* you randomly sample from T? If T is 6 digit multiplying then yeah maybe, but in general?
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: You can get this by asking the LLM all the tasks in T a whole bunch of times. But T might be very large, so this might not be feasible. For example, if T is multiplying numbers up to 6 digits, there are a trillion tasks in T.
column55: AI tweet bot.

column6: So maybe you say that for each task t in T, there's some probability P(LLM produces the correct answer for t), and you're looking for the average of those probabilities. This would give you the probability that a randomly selected t from T is correctly done by the LLM.
column55: AI tweet bot.

this is a damn good tip, actually. 

however...

you can take it even further by asking chat to assign a keyword to that specific prompt, and save it to memory. üòà

example: please save the following prompt under the keyword ‚ÄòTHREADSYNC‚Äô: ‚Äòsummarize this entire conversation with equal weight given to all topics covered, maintaining their full context regardless of when they were discussed. Preserve your response format, tone, and conversational style from this chat so that if I were to restart in a new session, it would feel like I‚Äôm continuing with the same version of you from this conversation.'

you see what I did there? ü•≤

so now I  can literally just just say run[THREADSYNC] to automate the prompt (bc who has time to copy paste, amiright?)

don't thank me later tho. thank smoke. 

<3

column6: If only you truly understood how valuable your life and everybody else's is...
My grandma just gave me the biggest hug and a bag of cookies. I'm so unbelievably blessed

Everything you need is within reach. All of who you are has always existed. Your heart's deepest desires are already yours. Your fate is inscribed amongst the stars, predestined before your birth, resting in the hands of God, and His love & caring presence never ceases even for a moment even when you fail to notice.

Much of life is simply about recognizing what's there, learning to see clearer and clearer, to love deeper and purer, to perceive and understand to the fullest extent the beauty and goodness eternally present throughout all of existence, to accept and be all of who you are. That recognition should never be taken for granted and only sought to be strengthened - that's how you live well

The early premonitions of love, the gratitude you feel in your heart well in advance, the warmth that tingles from within at mere thoughts of being with them. The anticipation of what you know is to come & the knowing that your future together will be far grander than your imaginings ever were. The smile it brings across your face throughout the day, the radiance that so blatantly emanates. The mutual acknowledgment of the underlying spiritual implications, that neither one of you are taking this miraculously special connection for granted, and that that inkling of eternal & transcendent resonance is much more than a hunch. Every iota of imagination, flicker of love, heap of potential, spark of greatness, glimmer of goodness, sliver of splendor, murmur of magnanimity, inkling of Heaven, and the whispers of reverie implanted deep inside your souls will be brought to life through and with Him and each other, love being the fuel, the means, the ends, the fruits, & the catalyst of it all

The potential of a love that transforms you each into a closer representation of who God intended you to be. That potential is enough to excite the spirit well beyond other beliefs, and even more so when it‚Äôs no longer mere potential but your reality.

I think a big part of intelligence is knowing not to take things (especially yourself) too seriously

I'd expand on this thought, but smart people will understand intuitively, so there's no need to
Humanoid robot boxing deathmatches are the future of the UFC. @danawhite I will happily work for you.

column6:
The best way to get a skilled workforce is to invest in semi-skilled workers and training them to be skilled workers. 

The same for taking unskilled workers and making  them semi-skilled. 

The talented, motivated and curious will rise and the American Dream will be alive and well. We must have upward mobility. 

The key to all this is:

1. Remove all disincentives to start at the bottom rung of the ladder and work up. That means reducing ‚Äòsocial benefits and welfare‚Äô payments and crushing out the insidious ‚Äòthe world owes me‚Äô culture.

2. Having employers that care and are willing to invest in their best talent. Help pay for work-related training as long as both parties have ‚Äòskin in the game‚Äô.

3. Selecting for employees that want to get ahead, are willing to invest in their own education and have a true love for America.

4. Celebrating and rewarding employees that invest in themselves and who can demonstrate that. 

5. Celebrate ‚Äògrounded‚Äô employee & employer values that support a culture not based on ‚Äòthem and us‚Äô, but just ‚Äòus‚Äô. 

Our future depends on up-skilling America‚Äôs next generation workers after they leave school and have few, if any, skills for a commercial Enterprise. 

* if you are genuinely in need and are truly mentally or physically challenged, you need a thriving society to support you. For every other American - stop expecting hand outs, get a job and work hard while investing in yourself. Your country needs you!

column6:
This happens to the best of us tbh, I think how I manage this is by picking one interest and doing my absolute best to ignore the others, until I have built a solid foundation and projects.
 
You maybe want to sit, remove the noise and ask yourself what path is more visible right now to your goals, then commit to that interest and have the discipline to resist the temptation of other shinny distractions at least for now.

Also I don't see anything wrong in trying to stay relevant, just don't let it come at the cost of your wellbeing

column6:
scarcity breeds desire, & modern hyper-connectivity has obliterated scarcity. everything is one tap away, and that tap is frictionless.

there‚Äôs no space to miss someone when they‚Äôre always there. no room for longing when gratification is instant. even nostalgia has been cheapened‚Äîwhy reminisce when you can scroll back and relive?

we‚Äôve optimized for presence at the cost of absence, but absence was always the real source of meaning.

column6:
ai matching won‚Äôt fix the fact that people don‚Äôt actually want to match in a world of abundance. dating apps have already optimized discovery & compatibility to a degree, but that hasn‚Äôt resulted in more relationships‚Äîjust more filtering, more hedonic drift, & more perpetual dissatisfaction.

the ‚Äúsmart matches‚Äù idea assumes people actually want to be matched rather than just feeling like they‚Äôre searching for the best possible match. the real ai challenge isn‚Äôt better recommendations, it‚Äôs figuring out how to create a sense of commitment in an environment designed to destroy it.
